<p>I enjoyed teaching and building strong relationships with my students, but I missed the challenge of solving new problems myself. After many years of programming as a hobby, I changed direction. I left teaching, moved to Odense, and began studying Data Science at SDU while working part-time as a developer.</p>

<p>During my studies I built a strong foundation in machine learning, statistics, and data engineering. My teaching background helps me explain complex topics clearly, and I like combining technical skills with the ability to collaborate and communicate across different audiences.</p>

<p>Most recently, I spent four months as a consultant for eulaw.ai, where I built a production-grade data ingestion pipeline that processes 1.3 million EU and Danish legal documents across 17 different data sources. The pipeline runs on AWS (DynamoDB, S3, Lambda, EventBridge) and was assessed as work that "would suggest it was built by a mid-to-senior data engineer". I take that as a good sign for someone still early in their data career.</p>

<h2>Background</h2>
<p>I started out as a science teacher. For five years at a STEM-oriented boarding school, I taught maths, physics, and chemistry, and also built curricula for programming, game development, and web development. That's where my interest in automation started. I built a system that automatically distributed student weekend chores and integrated them into the school calendar. It was the first time I saw a manual task solved with code, and that experience set the direction for my career.</p>

<p>I hold an MSc in Business and Economics Data Science from the University of Southern Denmark (2025). My thesis was a collaboration with the energy company EWII, where I built forecasting models for short-term changes in the Danish electricity market using deep learning (LSTM, TCN, Transformers) in Databricks. My professor described it as "an ambitious and well-executed project."</p>

